import java.util.ArrayDeque;
import java.util.Queue;

public int nearestExit(char[][] maze, int[] entrance) {
    int m = maze.length;
    int n = maze[0].length;
    int[][] moves = {{-1, 0}, {1, 0}, {0, -1}, {0, 1}};
    Queue<int[]> q = new ArrayDeque<>();
    q.offer(new int[]{entrance[0], entrance[1]});

    int steps = -1;
    while (!q.isEmpty()) {
        steps++;
        int size = q.size();
        for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
            int[] pos = q.poll();
            int r = pos[0];
            int c = pos[1];
            if (maze[r][c] == '+') continue;
            if (r == 0 || r == m-1 || c == 0 || c == n-1) {
                if (r != entrance[0] || c != entrance[1]) return steps;
            }
            maze[r][c] = '+';
            for (int[] move : moves) {
                int nr = r + move[0];
                int nc = c + move[1];
                if (nr >= 0 && nr < m && nc >= 0 && nc < n) {
                    q.offer(new int[]{nr, nc});
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return -1;
}
```

    The algorithm uses a breadth-first search (BFS) to explore the maze. It starts at the entrance and iterates through all possible moves (up, down, left, or right) until an exit cell is found. Each step in the BFS is counted by incrementing the `steps` variable. If no exit is found, the function returns `-1`.

The BFS queue stores the current position in the maze `{[row, col]}`. At every step, this position is dequeued from the queue, and we check if this cell is marked as a wall or a previously visited cell. If the current cell is located at any border of the maze and not the entrance cell, we can count it as an exit and return the `steps` value.

Next, we mark this cell as a wall (to avoid revisiting it), and we iterate through all possible neighboring positions. If any of these neighboring positions are within the maze dimensions and not a wall, they're added to the queue for future exploration.

The BFS will continue until the queue is empty or until an exit is found. When no more possibilities exist, the function returns `-1`.
